00:00:01.670 --> 00:00:04.270
Prof: So anyway,
the course I'm going to teach

00:00:04.270 --> 00:00:05.720
is called Financial Theory.
 

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:08.390
I'm going to teach an actual
class.

00:00:08.390 --> 00:00:10.494
I'm going to spend the first
half of the class talking about

00:00:10.494 --> 00:00:12.350
the course and why you might be
interested in it,

00:00:12.350 --> 00:00:13.710
and then I'm going to start
with the course.

00:00:13.710 --> 00:00:16.104
There are not that many
lectures available in the

00:00:16.104 --> 00:00:18.400
semester so I'm not going to
waste this one.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:20.815
So the first half of the class
is going to be about why to

00:00:20.815 --> 00:00:22.680
study it and the mechanics of
the course,

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:25.348
and the second half of the
lecture is going to be actually

00:00:25.348 --> 00:00:26.800
the first part of the course.
 

00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:29.795
It'll give you maybe an idea of
whether you'll find the course

00:00:29.795 --> 00:00:30.680
interesting too.
 

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:36.248
So I think I'll turn this--I
won't have too much PowerPoint

00:00:36.248 --> 00:00:36.920
here.
 

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:41.141
So you should know that finance
was not taught until ten years

00:00:41.141 --> 00:00:42.110
ago at Yale.
 

00:00:42.110 --> 00:00:46.605
It was regarded by the deans
and the classically minded

00:00:46.605 --> 00:00:51.517
faculty of the arts and sciences
as a vocational subject not

00:00:51.517 --> 00:00:55.680
worthy of being taught to Yale
undergraduates.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:58.230
It was growing more and more
famous,

00:00:58.230 --> 00:01:01.926
however, in the world and there
was a band of business school

00:01:01.926 --> 00:01:04.144
professors,
Fischer Black,

00:01:04.144 --> 00:01:07.239
Robert Merton,
William Sharpe,

00:01:07.239 --> 00:01:11.159
Steve Ross, Myron Scholes,
Merton Miller,

00:01:11.159 --> 00:01:14.209
who had a huge following in
business schools teaching the

00:01:14.209 --> 00:01:16.391
subject,
and whose students went off to

00:01:16.391 --> 00:01:19.159
Wall Street,
and more or less dominated the

00:01:19.159 --> 00:01:22.000
investment banking parts of Wall
Street,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.980
and became extremely successful.
 

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:29.510
Finance became the most highly
paid profession.

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:32.786
It became the most highly paid
faculty in the university,

00:01:32.786 --> 00:01:35.420
although they were all in
business schools.

00:01:35.420 --> 00:01:40.095
There are more physics PhDs
working in finance now than

00:01:40.095 --> 00:01:42.780
there are working in physics.
 

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:46.946
So this merry band of financial
theory professors didn't really

00:01:46.946 --> 00:01:48.560
believe in regulation.
 

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:53.819
They believed markets left
unfettered worked best of all.

00:01:53.819 --> 00:01:56.907
They believed in what they
called efficient markets and the

00:01:56.907 --> 00:01:59.888
idea that asset prices reflect
all the available possible

00:01:59.888 --> 00:02:00.739
information.
 

00:02:00.739 --> 00:02:03.006
So an implication of that is
that if you want to find out

00:02:03.006 --> 00:02:05.394
whether a company's doing well
or not you don't have to take

00:02:05.394 --> 00:02:07.540
the trouble to read all their
financial reports,

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.430
just look at their stock price.
 

00:02:09.430 --> 00:02:12.774
If you wanted to know whether a
country's doing well or not you

00:02:12.774 --> 00:02:15.901
don't have to study its entire
political system and current

00:02:15.901 --> 00:02:18.199
events,
just look at the general stock

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:20.620
market of the country and
that'll tell you.

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:23.518
They believed that you could
make as good returns in the

00:02:23.518 --> 00:02:26.627
market as a lay person as you
could as an expert because all

00:02:26.627 --> 00:02:29.683
the experts were competing to
try and get the best possible

00:02:29.683 --> 00:02:31.524
price,
and so the price itself

00:02:31.524 --> 00:02:34.485
reflected all their knowledge
and wisdom and opinions and so

00:02:34.485 --> 00:02:37.097
the lay person could take
advantage of that by buying

00:02:37.097 --> 00:02:37.699
stocks.
 

00:02:37.699 --> 00:02:39.990
Everybody should be an
investor, they felt.

00:02:39.990 --> 00:02:43.211
A monkey throwing darts at a
dart board would do as well as

00:02:43.211 --> 00:02:44.878
any of the greatest experts.
 

00:02:44.878 --> 00:02:48.979
Now, their own theory was
basically contradicted by their

00:02:48.979 --> 00:02:53.299
own experience because all of
them seemed to go out into the

00:02:53.299 --> 00:02:56.472
world and invest,
and almost all of them made

00:02:56.472 --> 00:02:59.885
extraordinary returns and made a
huge amount of money all of

00:02:59.885 --> 00:03:03.068
which made them even less
popular in the faculty of arts

00:03:03.068 --> 00:03:04.110
and sciences.
 

00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:07.828
So, a critical part of their
theory was that the markets were

00:03:07.828 --> 00:03:10.430
so efficient,
driven by people like them who

00:03:10.430 --> 00:03:12.740
are competing to exploit every
advantage,

00:03:12.740 --> 00:03:14.479
and therefore compete away
every advantage,

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:18.757
and by doing that put all the
information they have into the

00:03:18.757 --> 00:03:19.408
prices.
 

00:03:19.408 --> 00:03:22.316
The implication of that theory
is that there's an

00:03:22.316 --> 00:03:25.706
extraordinarily clever way of
computing the value of most

00:03:25.706 --> 00:03:28.467
investment assets,
and about deciding when a

00:03:28.467 --> 00:03:31.150
financial decision's a good
thing to do or not,

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:34.056
and that was the heart of what
they taught in these business

00:03:34.056 --> 00:03:36.611
schools,
these algorithms for valuing

00:03:36.611 --> 00:03:39.990
assets and making optimal
financial decisions.

00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:44.571
One striking thing is that the
people they studied,

00:03:44.571 --> 00:03:49.884
the business people and the
investment bankers they studied

00:03:49.884 --> 00:03:52.360
adopted their language.
 

00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:55.220
So this had never happened in
academia before.

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:59.163
I mean, anthropologists study
primitive tribes and different

00:03:59.163 --> 00:04:02.639
kinds of people all the time and
not one of them,

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:05.320
I venture to say,
has ever taken over all the

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:08.062
language invented by
anthropologists to behave

00:04:08.062 --> 00:04:10.438
themselves in their own
societies,

00:04:10.438 --> 00:04:15.085
but the business people that
these professors were studying

00:04:15.085 --> 00:04:19.730
ended up using exactly the
language created in academia.

00:04:19.730 --> 00:04:21.000
Now, Yale was very different.
 

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.074
There was no divide between
economists and finance people,

00:04:26.074 --> 00:04:29.370
the business school finance
people.

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:33.737
At Yale the greatest economists
in Yale's history were actually

00:04:33.737 --> 00:04:35.779
very interested in finance.
 

00:04:35.779 --> 00:04:37.680
Maybe they were financial
economists to begin with.

00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:40.360
So the greatest Yale economist
of the first half of the

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:43.490
twentieth century was Irving
Fisher who you hear a lot about.

00:04:43.490 --> 00:04:46.821
He wrote, possibly,
the first economics PhD at

00:04:46.821 --> 00:04:47.339
Yale.
 

00:04:47.339 --> 00:04:50.901
There was no economist to teach
him so he had to write his PhD

00:04:50.901 --> 00:04:54.639
with Gibbs, maybe the greatest
American physicist of the time.

00:04:54.639 --> 00:04:56.303
There's a building,
as you know,

00:04:56.303 --> 00:04:58.290
on Science Hill named after
Gibbs,

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:03.050
and you'll hear more about his
dissertation in the 1890s,

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:05.300
but he was a mathematical
economist,

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:08.553
an econometrician but he
invented almost all of this

00:05:08.553 --> 00:05:10.980
economics in order to study
finance.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:14.028
The most famous Yale economist
of the second half of the

00:05:14.028 --> 00:05:16.079
twentieth century was James
Tobin,

00:05:16.079 --> 00:05:20.230
a famous macroeconomist,
the most famous macroeconomist,

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:23.334
possibly, of the second half of
the twentieth century after

00:05:23.334 --> 00:05:25.019
Keynes,
a great Keynesian.

00:05:25.019 --> 00:05:28.622
But he got the Nobel Prize for
work he did on finance in

00:05:28.622 --> 00:05:29.410
economics.
 

00:05:29.410 --> 00:05:32.120
Finance was incredibly
interesting to him.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:36.043
So Bob Shiller and I went to
Yale and we basically said to

00:05:36.043 --> 00:05:39.416
the deans,
"There's a long tradition

00:05:39.416 --> 00:05:43.379
of finance and economics
hand-in-hand at Yale,

00:05:43.379 --> 00:05:46.639
and so it's not a vocational
subject.

00:05:46.639 --> 00:05:48.925
It's actually central to
economics, and central to

00:05:48.925 --> 00:05:51.446
understanding the economy,
and central to understanding

00:05:51.446 --> 00:05:52.519
the global economy.
 

00:05:52.519 --> 00:05:55.600
So we'd like to teach it to
Yale undergraduates,

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:58.291
and we believe a few of them
will actually take the

00:05:58.291 --> 00:06:00.658
course,"
and so they agreed to let us do

00:06:00.658 --> 00:06:03.216
it,
and so we've been teaching it

00:06:03.216 --> 00:06:05.269
now for the last ten years.
 

00:06:05.269 --> 00:06:12.083
So as you know Shiller has been
very critical of the business

00:06:12.083 --> 00:06:15.490
efficient markets tradition.
 

00:06:15.490 --> 00:06:18.149
He feels that these finance
professors left something

00:06:18.149 --> 00:06:19.939
essential out of the whole
story.

00:06:19.939 --> 00:06:22.319
What they left out was
psychology.

00:06:22.319 --> 00:06:25.490
They left out the idea of fads,
and rumors,

00:06:25.490 --> 00:06:28.911
and narratives,
which he thinks has as big an

00:06:28.911 --> 00:06:33.420
effect on prices as the hard
information about profits that

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:37.930
the business school professors
imagined drove profits.

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:42.458
I myself have been quite
critical of the financial

00:06:42.458 --> 00:06:43.290
theory.
 

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:50.209
I started off as a straight
pure mathematical economist.

00:06:50.209 --> 00:06:53.492
To me economics was almost a
branch of logic and philosophy

00:06:53.492 --> 00:06:56.550
that happened to tell you
something about the world.

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:00.942
So I got my PhD with Ken Arrow,
who you'll hear a lot about

00:07:00.942 --> 00:07:02.079
very shortly.
 

00:07:02.079 --> 00:07:05.204
And I came to Yale,
I'd been a Yale undergraduate,

00:07:05.204 --> 00:07:08.838
I came back to Yale and I
joined the Cowles Foundation.

00:07:08.838 --> 00:07:12.110
And the Cowles Foundation's
motto was basically,

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:15.449
"Can we make economics
more mathematical?

00:07:15.449 --> 00:07:18.908
Economics, a social science,
ought to be amenable to

00:07:18.908 --> 00:07:23.045
mathematical analysis just like
physics or chemistry is,"

00:07:23.045 --> 00:07:26.028
and people didn't believe this
at first.

00:07:26.028 --> 00:07:29.531
And the Cowles Foundation,
which you'll hear a lot about

00:07:29.531 --> 00:07:33.961
in these lectures,
led the revolution in economics

00:07:33.961 --> 00:07:37.949
transforming it from a verbal
subject,

00:07:37.949 --> 00:07:41.170
political economy,
into a mathematical subject.

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:45.300
Well, I decided around 1989
that since I did mathematical

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.351
economics,
and there were all these

00:07:47.351 --> 00:07:50.079
finance people doing all kinds
of mathematical things on Wall

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:51.990
Street and doing it very
successfully,

00:07:51.990 --> 00:07:54.250
I thought I might just check
out what they were doing.

00:07:54.250 --> 00:07:56.540
So it might be fun to see what
they were up to.

00:07:56.540 --> 00:08:00.471
So I went to Wall Street and I
joined--most people I knew,

00:08:00.471 --> 00:08:03.990
in fact, professors I knew went
to Goldman Sachs.

00:08:03.990 --> 00:08:07.137
There was a famous finance
professor, who I had mentioned

00:08:07.137 --> 00:08:10.452
before, named Fischer Black who
was there at the time and he

00:08:10.452 --> 00:08:12.139
attracted a lot of people.
 

00:08:12.139 --> 00:08:13.769
And so that was the traditional
thing to do,

00:08:13.769 --> 00:08:16.293
but I decided to go to a
littler firm called Kidder

00:08:16.293 --> 00:08:19.584
Peabody,
and it was the seventh biggest

00:08:19.584 --> 00:08:22.230
investment bank at the time.
 

00:08:22.230 --> 00:08:25.850
And one thing led to another,
and they decided that they

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:29.404
wanted to reorganize their
research department in fixed

00:08:29.404 --> 00:08:30.129
income.
 

00:08:30.129 --> 00:08:32.174
And since I was a professor
there, and I did mathematical

00:08:32.174 --> 00:08:33.663
economics,
and I was there for the whole

00:08:33.663 --> 00:08:35.779
year somebody said,
the director of the Fixed

00:08:35.779 --> 00:08:38.850
Income Department said,
"Why don't you take charge

00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:41.902
of it and hire a new Fixed
Income Research Department for

00:08:41.902 --> 00:08:42.230
me.
 

00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:46.936
So I did, and ultimately there
were seventy-five people in the

00:08:46.936 --> 00:08:47.940
department.
 

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:50.428
All the time I was a professor
at Yale.

00:08:50.428 --> 00:08:54.779
And after five years Kidder
Peabody,

00:08:54.779 --> 00:08:57.240
even though it was a hundred
thirty-five years old,

00:08:57.240 --> 00:09:01.200
formed by a famous family,
the name should sound--

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.941
Peabody--familiar to you,
it closed down after a hundred

00:09:04.941 --> 00:09:08.038
thirty-five years,
five years after I got there.

00:09:08.038 --> 00:09:10.778
I had to invite the
seventy-five people I'd hired

00:09:10.778 --> 00:09:13.690
into my office and say,
"You're fired."

00:09:13.690 --> 00:09:16.663
And then I went next door to
the office next to mine and the

00:09:16.663 --> 00:09:18.830
guy there said,
"You're fired."

00:09:18.830 --> 00:09:22.940
And so that was my first taste
of Wall Street.

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:26.269
And after that six of us
founded a hedge fund called

00:09:26.269 --> 00:09:32.023
Ellington Capital Management,
which was a mortgage hedge

00:09:32.023 --> 00:09:36.740
fund, and we had--
I'll tell you a lot about it.

00:09:36.740 --> 00:09:41.519
It started after the Kidder
closing as a rather small hedge

00:09:41.519 --> 00:09:43.688
fund,
but it grew into a very big

00:09:43.688 --> 00:09:46.105
mortgage hedge fund,
in fact the biggest mortgage

00:09:46.105 --> 00:09:47.250
hedge fund in the country.
 

00:09:47.250 --> 00:09:50.230
(Although recently we found out
that practically everybody who

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:52.428
trades mortgages is basically a
hedge fund.

00:09:52.428 --> 00:09:54.301
Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac,
they'll all basically hedge

00:09:54.301 --> 00:09:56.245
funds, so it doesn't mean
anything anymore to say that

00:09:56.245 --> 00:09:57.639
you're a big mortgage hedge
fund.)

00:09:57.639 --> 00:10:01.379
But anyway, we almost went out
of business in '98 a subject,

00:10:01.379 --> 00:10:03.168
a story I'll tell you at great
length,

00:10:03.168 --> 00:10:06.724
and then we just suffered
through this disastrous last

00:10:06.724 --> 00:10:09.240
year or two,
but we're still here.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:12.508
So these experiences,
of course, have colored my

00:10:12.508 --> 00:10:16.820
understanding of Wall Street and
my approach to the subject.

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:19.174
So I took on,
in my theoretical work,

00:10:19.174 --> 00:10:22.250
finance and economic theory on
its own terms.

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:25.090
I didn't think like Shiller to
introduce psychology into

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:27.363
economics I just take it on in
its own terms,

00:10:27.363 --> 00:10:29.120
in its own mathematical terms.
 

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:32.788
And what I found was that there
are two things missing in the

00:10:32.788 --> 00:10:33.889
Standard Theory.
 

00:10:33.889 --> 00:10:37.662
One is that it implicitly
assumes you can buy insurance

00:10:37.662 --> 00:10:38.850
for everything.
 

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:40.990
It's the assumption that's
called complete markets.

00:10:40.990 --> 00:10:45.210
And secondly it leaves out
collateral entirely so you'll

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:49.047
never see, almost in any single
economics textbook,

00:10:49.047 --> 00:10:52.038
the idea of collateral or
leverage.

00:10:52.038 --> 00:10:54.490
And those, I think,
the idea that you can't get

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:57.529
insurance for everything and
that you need collateral,

00:10:57.529 --> 00:10:59.908
you know, you have to be able
to convince someone you're going

00:10:59.908 --> 00:11:02.325
to pay them back if you borrow
money and collateral is the most

00:11:02.325 --> 00:11:04.860
convincing way of persuading him
he's going to be paid back,

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:05.678
the lender.
 

00:11:05.678 --> 00:11:08.350
Those two things were missing
from the Standard Theory,

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:15.370
so I built a theory around
incomplete markets and leverage,

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:18.120
which is a critique of the
Standard Theory.

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:24.970
So in a way Shiller and I have
been vindicated by the crash.

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:31.278
I mean, so let me just show you
a picture here.

00:11:31.278 --> 00:11:36.091
Well, maybe I will,
you know, how bad the crash

00:11:36.091 --> 00:11:36.720
was.
 

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:41.908
So let's look at the Dow Jones.
 

00:11:41.908 --> 00:11:45.817
The Dow Jones is an average of
thirty stocks and what their

00:11:45.817 --> 00:11:46.559
value is.
 

00:11:46.559 --> 00:11:48.230
We'll talk more about it later.
 

00:11:48.230 --> 00:11:52.650
But here it is back to 1913
moving along breezily going up

00:11:52.650 --> 00:11:57.441
and up and up,
you know, there are a few blips

00:11:57.441 --> 00:12:03.038
which we'll come to later like
this one in 1929,

00:12:03.038 --> 00:12:04.820
and then--but look what
happened lately.

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:05.649
Look at that.
 

00:12:05.649 --> 00:12:09.062
The Dow Jones was up at 14,000
and it dropped to 6,500,

00:12:09.062 --> 00:12:12.225
something like that,
more than a fifty percent drop

00:12:12.225 --> 00:12:15.070
and now it's gone fifty percent
up again.

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:18.504
So if you believe these finance
professors you'd have to say

00:12:18.504 --> 00:12:21.879
that everybody realized that
future profits in America were

00:12:21.879 --> 00:12:25.490
going to be less than half what
they thought they were going to

00:12:25.490 --> 00:12:28.750
be before and that's why the
stock market dropped.

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:31.514
And then miraculously when it
hit a bottom everybody figured,

00:12:31.514 --> 00:12:33.590
"Oh, my gosh,
we misunderstood things.

00:12:33.590 --> 00:12:36.254
Actually it's not nearly that
bad and things are fifty percent

00:12:36.254 --> 00:12:38.787
higher because now people think
that profits really weren't

00:12:38.787 --> 00:12:40.759
going to go,
you know, didn't drop in half,

00:12:40.759 --> 00:12:42.922
didn't drop by fifty percent,
they only dropped by

00:12:42.922 --> 00:12:43.860
twenty-five percent.
 

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:46.058
And that was the only way,
according to the old theory,

00:12:46.058 --> 00:12:47.158
to explain what happened.
 

00:12:47.158 --> 00:12:49.956
Now Shiller would just say,
"Well,

00:12:49.956 --> 00:12:52.090
everybody's--they're crazy.
 

00:12:52.090 --> 00:12:54.698
They got this into their head
that the world was just going to

00:12:54.698 --> 00:12:56.408
be great and then some rumor
started,

00:12:56.408 --> 00:12:58.952
and things were so high,
and the narrative changed and

00:12:58.952 --> 00:13:00.826
they thought things were
terrible,"

00:13:00.826 --> 00:13:01.928
and this his story.
 

00:13:01.928 --> 00:13:03.600
And I'm not sure how he gets it
to go up again.

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:10.480
They changed their mind again.
 

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:17.100
By the way it's a little bit
better to look at the Dow

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:24.595
correcting for inflation and
then you see that the 1929 crash

00:13:24.595 --> 00:13:28.150
looks--
and this is on a log scale,

00:13:28.150 --> 00:13:33.000
remember before the Depression
the stock market was so low.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.048
It's grown so much over a
hundred years that it hardly

00:13:35.048 --> 00:13:36.480
seemed like anything was
happening.

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:40.917
Well, now in log scale--going
up two of these is multiplying

00:13:40.917 --> 00:13:43.636
by ten--
you see that in the Depression

00:13:43.636 --> 00:13:47.179
in 1929 through the early '30s
the stock market fell.

00:13:47.179 --> 00:13:48.408
I don't remember what it is.
 

00:13:48.408 --> 00:13:50.009
It looks like it's almost two
things.

00:13:50.009 --> 00:13:52.895
It looks like it's eighty or
ninety percent,

00:13:52.895 --> 00:13:55.849
and the fall this time has been
much smaller,

00:13:55.849 --> 00:13:58.399
fifty percent,
not ninety percent.

00:13:58.399 --> 00:14:04.740
So it's a whole thing down but
not two things down.

00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:05.769
It's not a whole thing down.
 

00:14:05.769 --> 00:14:06.470
It's less than that.
 

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:10.570
A whole thing down would be the
square root of ten or a third.

00:14:10.570 --> 00:14:11.720
It didn't go down two thirds.
 

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:12.980
It went down less than two
thirds.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:16.375
It went down fifty percent,
so the actual percentage drop

00:14:16.375 --> 00:14:19.408
was much worse in the Depression
than it is now.

00:14:19.408 --> 00:14:21.470
We're going to come back to all
these things.

00:14:21.470 --> 00:14:23.278
What else can we get out of
these numbers?

00:14:23.278 --> 00:14:27.840
I just want you to notice a
couple other things.

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:29.320
So these numbers are all very
interesting.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:32.245
If you're mathematical these
are the sorts of things you pay

00:14:32.245 --> 00:14:32.990
attention to.
 

00:14:32.990 --> 00:14:36.053
So these efficient markets
guys, they looked at the change

00:14:36.053 --> 00:14:37.288
in price every month.
 

00:14:37.288 --> 00:14:39.470
So there's a lot to say for
their theory.

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:41.370
They said, "Look,
it goes up and down

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:42.158
randomly."
 

00:14:42.158 --> 00:14:44.477
In fact we'll see that there
are all kinds of tests about

00:14:44.477 --> 00:14:46.879
whether you can predict it's
going to go up tomorrow on the

00:14:46.879 --> 00:14:49.350
basis of how it did yesterday,
and the answer's no.

00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:51.808
It's very difficult to predict
whether the stock market is

00:14:51.808 --> 00:14:52.629
going up or down.
 

00:14:52.629 --> 00:14:54.129
It seems to be random.
 

00:14:54.129 --> 00:14:57.764
Well, it's random and they used
to think it was normally

00:14:57.764 --> 00:14:58.690
distributed.
 

00:14:58.690 --> 00:15:01.014
A lot of people argued it was
normally distributed,

00:15:01.014 --> 00:15:01.759
but it's hard.
 

00:15:01.759 --> 00:15:05.259
You never get these gigantic
outliers if things are normally

00:15:05.259 --> 00:15:06.090
distributed.
 

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:08.269
They're just way too unlikely
to happen.

00:15:08.269 --> 00:15:10.807
So Mandelbrot,
who was a Yale professor who

00:15:10.807 --> 00:15:13.534
retired a couple years ago,
although he wasn't when he

00:15:13.534 --> 00:15:15.666
formed his theories,
the inventor of fractals,

00:15:15.666 --> 00:15:18.542
he said this couldn't possibly
be a random walk in the

00:15:18.542 --> 00:15:21.690
traditional Brownian motion
sense of the word because you'd

00:15:21.690 --> 00:15:25.610
never get these big outliers,
but he offered no explanation

00:15:25.610 --> 00:15:28.945
for why they might be there,
and I don't know if Shiller has

00:15:28.945 --> 00:15:29.870
an explanation either.
 

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:32.418
I mean, is it that people
suddenly get shocked one day and

00:15:32.418 --> 00:15:35.144
then the next week they change
their mind and things aren't so

00:15:35.144 --> 00:15:35.950
bad after all?
 

00:15:35.950 --> 00:15:40.913
But you'll see that the theory
of collateral and margins does

00:15:40.913 --> 00:15:43.559
explain these kinds of things.
 

00:15:43.559 --> 00:15:46.100
Let's just look at the Dow.
 

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:47.389
We just looked at the Dow.
 

00:15:47.389 --> 00:15:58.350
Let's look at another,
the S&amp;P 500.

00:15:58.350 --> 00:15:59.879
Where's the S&amp;P 500?
 

00:15:59.879 --> 00:16:12.539
 
 

00:16:12.539 --> 00:16:15.028
Here's the S&amp;P 500 data.
 

00:16:15.028 --> 00:16:16.678
Here's the history of the
S&amp;P 500.

00:16:16.678 --> 00:16:20.312
It looks very similar to the
Dow, except we have longer

00:16:20.312 --> 00:16:23.812
history back to 1871,
so I just want to point out one

00:16:23.812 --> 00:16:26.100
more thing in the S&amp;P 500.
 

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:28.538
So this is an average of
five-hundred stocks,

00:16:28.538 --> 00:16:31.308
not just thirty,
but it's more or less the same.

00:16:31.308 --> 00:16:36.808
But let's look at the same
thing taking the logarithm and

00:16:36.808 --> 00:16:38.970
check for inflation.
 

00:16:38.970 --> 00:16:44.399
So you see here that there are
these four cycles.

00:16:44.399 --> 00:16:46.149
Things seemed low in 1871.
 

00:16:46.149 --> 00:16:47.370
They go up and they go down.
 

00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:48.850
Then you've got another up and
a down.

00:16:48.850 --> 00:16:50.230
Then you've got another up and
a down.

00:16:50.230 --> 00:16:51.460
Then you've another up and a
down.

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:53.460
Four times the same thing has
happened.

00:16:53.460 --> 00:16:56.330
Now this could be just
meaningless accidents,

00:16:56.330 --> 00:17:02.519
but it will turn out that the
demography of the country,

00:17:02.519 --> 00:17:05.259
the baby boom cycle,
we haven't had just one baby

00:17:05.259 --> 00:17:09.073
boom we've had four of them,
so this cycle of stock prices,

00:17:09.073 --> 00:17:12.068
which they're each time a
generation long,

00:17:12.068 --> 00:17:14.558
happens to correspond exactly
to the rise,

00:17:14.558 --> 00:17:17.970
the different age distribution
in the population.

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:19.920
So another theory of the stock
market,

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:23.999
which wouldn't have been
entertained by these original

00:17:23.999 --> 00:17:26.684
financial theorists,
is that demography has

00:17:26.684 --> 00:17:28.348
something to do with the stock
market,

00:17:28.348 --> 00:17:31.352
not information about profits
and returns but the distribution

00:17:31.352 --> 00:17:32.730
of ages in the population.
 

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:35.410
So I'm not saying this theory
is correct,

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:37.618
although I was one of the
proponents of it,

00:17:37.618 --> 00:17:42.818
but it shows that there's room,
I think,

00:17:42.818 --> 00:17:48.588
in finance for economic things,
for demography to matter,

00:17:48.588 --> 00:17:53.349
for leverage to matter and not
just for expectations about

00:17:53.349 --> 00:17:54.769
future profits.
 

00:17:54.769 --> 00:17:57.298
So let me show you another
picture.

00:17:57.298 --> 00:18:00.730
So this is a second way in
which Shiller became famous.

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:04.632
He said, "Well,
look at housing prices,"

00:18:04.632 --> 00:18:07.259
the Case Shiller Housing Index.
 

00:18:07.259 --> 00:18:09.782
So he's also famous because he
had the idea of collecting

00:18:09.782 --> 00:18:10.548
housing prices.
 

00:18:10.548 --> 00:18:15.259
So it's quite amazing,
every town has to record,

00:18:15.259 --> 00:18:19.588
by law you have to record in
the town directory,

00:18:19.588 --> 00:18:22.151
and they're often on the
internet, what the price is of

00:18:22.151 --> 00:18:23.480
every sale of every house.
 

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:26.173
So everybody has it and it's
all publicly available on the

00:18:26.173 --> 00:18:28.585
internet, or most of it is
publicly available on the

00:18:28.585 --> 00:18:29.200
internet.
 

00:18:29.200 --> 00:18:32.327
And nobody thought to gather
all this information together

00:18:32.327 --> 00:18:35.674
and take the average and write
down an index until Shiller did

00:18:35.674 --> 00:18:36.059
it.
 

00:18:36.059 --> 00:18:40.048
So here's the Shiller Index.
 

00:18:40.048 --> 00:18:43.267
All right, so you can see that
housing prices were pretty

00:18:43.267 --> 00:18:46.599
stable throughout the '80s and
then in and around 2000 they

00:18:46.599 --> 00:18:49.041
started taking off,
so this is when the stock

00:18:49.041 --> 00:18:50.190
market was taking off too.
 

00:18:50.190 --> 00:18:52.390
So Shiller says this is
irrational exuberance.

00:18:52.390 --> 00:18:53.640
People just went crazy.
 

00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:55.190
They somehow think things can
never go down,

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:56.470
and they're just going to keep
going up,

00:18:56.470 --> 00:18:58.096
and they keep buying because
they think things are going to

00:18:58.096 --> 00:19:02.108
go up,
and it's crazy.

00:19:02.108 --> 00:19:05.200
Psychology--eventually a new
narrative is going to start.

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:06.790
Somebody's going to say,
"Oh, they've been going up

00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:07.920
so long they can't continue to
go up.

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:13.108
Things have to go down,"
and things went down.

00:19:13.108 --> 00:19:16.224
I think there's something to
psychology so there was

00:19:16.224 --> 00:19:19.278
something missing in the
original finance story.

00:19:19.278 --> 00:19:21.203
The finance guys,
by the way, they would say,

00:19:21.203 --> 00:19:23.130
"Well, the rise is not so
surprising.

00:19:23.130 --> 00:19:24.690
Look at the mortgage rates.
 

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:26.587
(This is the interest rate you
have to pay if you get a

00:19:26.587 --> 00:19:27.009
mortgage.)
 

00:19:27.009 --> 00:19:31.494
There's been an incredible
decline in mortgage rates over

00:19:31.494 --> 00:19:35.338
the years, so it's less costly
to buy housing.

00:19:35.338 --> 00:19:42.074
If you take the present value
of your expenditures you just

00:19:42.074 --> 00:19:44.279
have to pay less.
 

00:19:44.279 --> 00:19:46.318
You pay over a long period of
time,

00:19:46.318 --> 00:19:49.003
and so the interest rate is
less, so the value of the houses

00:19:49.003 --> 00:19:51.689
is worth more because you're
discounting the future benefits

00:19:51.689 --> 00:19:52.598
at a lower rate.
 

00:19:52.598 --> 00:19:54.240
(You'll hear all about
discounting later.)

00:19:54.240 --> 00:19:55.480
So there's no mystery."
 

00:19:55.480 --> 00:19:58.538
On the other hand nothing
happened to interest rates.

00:19:58.538 --> 00:20:01.287
They kept getting lower so
there's no reason why the market

00:20:01.287 --> 00:20:02.328
should have crashed.
 

00:20:02.328 --> 00:20:05.298
So, again, this seems like a
vindication for Shiller.

00:20:05.298 --> 00:20:08.892
Now, it also,
in a way, is a vindication for

00:20:08.892 --> 00:20:12.150
my theory which is
non-psychological.

00:20:12.150 --> 00:20:15.595
So I'm distrustful a little bit
of psychology because it can be

00:20:15.595 --> 00:20:18.038
anything, although I agree it's
important.

00:20:18.038 --> 00:20:22.308
So my theory is when you take a
loan you have to negotiate two

00:20:22.308 --> 00:20:26.720
things, the interest rate and
how much collateral you put up.

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:28.578
Who's going to trust you to pay
back?

00:20:28.578 --> 00:20:31.169
When you buy a house they say,
"You can't just borrow the

00:20:31.169 --> 00:20:32.568
whole value of the house."
 

00:20:32.568 --> 00:20:34.845
They say, "Well,
make a down payment of twenty

00:20:34.845 --> 00:20:35.298
percent.
 

00:20:35.298 --> 00:20:37.630
Borrow eighty percent of the
value of a house."

00:20:37.630 --> 00:20:40.250
And so what I say is that
instead of paying all your

00:20:40.250 --> 00:20:43.588
attention to the interest rate
think about the collateral rate.

00:20:43.588 --> 00:20:46.318
Why is it twenty percent that
you have to put down?

00:20:46.318 --> 00:20:48.779
Maybe it should be ten percent
or forty percent.

00:20:48.779 --> 00:20:50.965
Well, in fact,
that number changes all the

00:20:50.965 --> 00:20:51.338
time.
 

00:20:51.338 --> 00:20:55.704
So here what I've done is--the
pink line from 2000 to the

00:20:55.704 --> 00:20:59.445
future, that pink line is
Shiller's Housing Index

00:20:59.445 --> 00:21:00.460
inverted.
 

00:21:00.460 --> 00:21:05.299
So you notice the scale on the
right is the housing prices,

00:21:05.299 --> 00:21:09.640
but I've inverted it,
and on the left I have the down

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:11.559
payment percentage.
 

00:21:11.559 --> 00:21:16.338
These are non-agency loans.
 

00:21:16.338 --> 00:21:17.210
We'll come back to the graph
later--

00:21:17.210 --> 00:21:19.308
I don't have time to explain
exactly how I got it--

00:21:19.308 --> 00:21:22.519
but what you see is that from
2000 onwards the down payment

00:21:22.519 --> 00:21:25.730
people were asked to make to buy
their house got lower,

00:21:25.730 --> 00:21:28.873
and lower, and lower,
and lower and it got down to

00:21:28.873 --> 00:21:29.900
three percent.
 

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:32.638
You could put down three
percent of the value of the

00:21:32.638 --> 00:21:35.487
house and borrow the other
ninety-seven percent of the

00:21:35.487 --> 00:21:37.259
value of the house to buy it.
 

00:21:37.259 --> 00:21:41.208
So amazingly the prices go up
and down just with what's called

00:21:41.208 --> 00:21:42.180
the leverage.
 

00:21:42.180 --> 00:21:44.048
So why is it called leverage?
 

00:21:44.048 --> 00:21:46.690
Because the cash you put down
payment,

00:21:46.690 --> 00:21:48.625
say ten percent,
you can lever it up and own an

00:21:48.625 --> 00:21:50.983
asset that's worth a hundred
even though you put down ten

00:21:50.983 --> 00:21:51.490
dollars.
 

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:52.538
So you're leveraged 10:1.
 

00:21:52.538 --> 00:21:56.250
If you put down three dollars
and you get a hundred dollar

00:21:56.250 --> 00:21:58.920
house you've leveraged it 30:1
or 33:1.

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:00.118
So that's why it's called
leverage.

00:22:00.118 --> 00:22:03.588
So anyway, the point is that
leverage went way up.

00:22:03.588 --> 00:22:06.568
The margins kept going down and
down and down and just at the

00:22:06.568 --> 00:22:09.612
peak of the housing cycle,
which is the bottom of that

00:22:09.612 --> 00:22:12.933
curve, that's when collateral
started getting tougher and

00:22:12.933 --> 00:22:16.019
people started asking for more
money down again,

00:22:16.019 --> 00:22:18.250
and sure enough the prices
turned around.

00:22:18.250 --> 00:22:20.858
So if you look at the prices of
mortgages,

00:22:20.858 --> 00:22:24.118
again, the inverse on the
right, and you look at the

00:22:24.118 --> 00:22:27.145
margins on the left,
not for buying houses but for

00:22:27.145 --> 00:22:29.077
buying securities--
I don't have time to explain

00:22:29.077 --> 00:22:31.886
this whole graph,
but the blue line is the buying

00:22:31.886 --> 00:22:32.750
securities.
 

00:22:32.750 --> 00:22:35.500
So '98 is a big crisis,
the margins spike up,

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:38.250
I don't have pricing data back
until then.

00:22:38.250 --> 00:22:39.259
That's the blue line.
 

00:22:39.259 --> 00:22:43.548
And now from 2007 to 2009 you
see the margins spiking up.

00:22:43.548 --> 00:22:47.817
So to buy a toxic mortgage
security investors don't pay

00:22:47.817 --> 00:22:51.608
cash, they borrow part of the
money to buy it.

00:22:51.608 --> 00:22:54.710
They used to put down only five
percent to buy it.

00:22:54.710 --> 00:22:57.755
Now they have to put down
seventy percent to buy it on

00:22:57.755 --> 00:22:58.329
average.
 

00:22:58.329 --> 00:23:00.470
Well, what happened to prices?
 

00:23:00.470 --> 00:23:04.172
Prices--this is the inverse of
prices--in 2007 they started to

00:23:04.172 --> 00:23:04.838
collapse.
 

00:23:04.838 --> 00:23:07.578
So this going up means prices
are collapsing.

00:23:07.578 --> 00:23:10.037
So once again,
the margins--tougher margins

00:23:10.037 --> 00:23:13.489
means lower prices and as the
margins came down recently the

00:23:13.489 --> 00:23:15.420
prices have gone up recently.
 

00:23:15.420 --> 00:23:22.509
So it's an alternative theory.
 

00:23:22.509 --> 00:23:31.160
So what else do I want to show
you?

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:36.188
So it doesn't mean that the
standard financial theory is

00:23:36.188 --> 00:23:36.920
wrong.
 

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:38.788
After all, I helped run a hedge
fund.

00:23:38.788 --> 00:23:41.690
Six of us founded it and we've
been in business for fifteen

00:23:41.690 --> 00:23:42.088
years.
 

00:23:42.088 --> 00:23:44.880
We must believe in standard
financial theory because that's

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:46.950
how we've been making a lot of
our money.

00:23:46.950 --> 00:23:49.214
We exploit all those algorithms
and those are the things I'm

00:23:49.214 --> 00:23:52.532
going to teach you,
so I certainly believe it and

00:23:52.532 --> 00:23:57.650
it's very important to teach you
that again this semester,

00:23:57.650 --> 00:24:01.210
but there's more to the theory
than just that.

