00:36:12.960 --> 00:36:15.447
Benno Schmidt,
he suddenly noticed that there

00:36:15.447 --> 00:36:18.086
was deferred maintenance,
as he called it,

00:36:18.086 --> 00:36:21.059
a billion dollars to fix the
Yale buildings.

00:36:21.059 --> 00:36:23.552
That's why, incidentally,
every year another college gets

00:36:23.552 --> 00:36:23.909
fixed.
 

00:36:23.909 --> 00:36:26.244
They decided there was deferred
maintenance of a billion

00:36:26.244 --> 00:36:26.670
dollars.
 

00:36:26.670 --> 00:36:30.402
A hundred million dollars every
year for ten years had to be

00:36:30.402 --> 00:36:30.909
spent.
 

00:36:30.909 --> 00:36:33.237
The whole endowment then was
three billion,

00:36:33.237 --> 00:36:36.284
and now we had a one billion
dollar deferred maintenance

00:36:36.284 --> 00:36:36.949
problem.
 

00:36:36.949 --> 00:36:39.179
The budget was about one
billion then.

00:36:39.179 --> 00:36:42.869
So how much should you cut the
Yale budget at that time?

00:36:42.869 --> 00:36:45.152
So Benno Schmidt said,
"I'm firing fifteen

00:36:45.152 --> 00:36:46.690
percent of the faculty."
 

00:36:46.690 --> 00:36:48.820
He announced he was firing
fifteen percent of the faculty.

00:36:48.820 --> 00:36:51.155
That was on the front page of
the New York Times,

00:36:51.155 --> 00:36:52.590
"Yale to fire
faculty."

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:56.800
Well, did he make the right
decision?

00:36:56.800 --> 00:37:02.527
Rick Levin took over as
president three months later,

00:37:02.527 --> 00:37:04.510
so probably not.
 

00:37:04.510 --> 00:37:07.010
What mistake did he make in his
calculations?

00:37:07.010 --> 00:37:07.940
What should he have done?
 

00:37:07.940 --> 00:37:09.769
What was the right response?
 

00:37:09.769 --> 00:37:13.039
We're going to talk about it.
 

00:37:13.039 --> 00:37:15.940
It's not that hard a problem.
 

00:37:15.940 --> 00:37:20.409
Now, let's take a slightly more
complicated one.

00:37:20.409 --> 00:37:21.739
You're a bookie.
 

00:37:21.739 --> 00:37:25.090
The World Series is coming up.
 

00:37:25.090 --> 00:37:26.639
The Yankees are playing the
Dodgers,

00:37:26.639 --> 00:37:30.708
let's say, and you know that
the teams are evenly matched and

00:37:30.708 --> 00:37:34.775
you've got a bunch of friends
who you know every game will be

00:37:34.775 --> 00:37:38.844
willing to bet at even odds on
either side because they think

00:37:38.844 --> 00:37:40.199
it's a tossup.
 

00:37:40.199 --> 00:37:42.384
Well, one of your customers
comes to you and says,

00:37:42.384 --> 00:37:44.568
he's a Yankee fan,
he's sure the Yankees are going

00:37:44.568 --> 00:37:45.550
to win the series.
 

00:37:45.550 --> 00:37:49.478
He's willing to put up three
hundred thousand dollars to bet

00:37:49.478 --> 00:37:50.610
on the Yankees.
 

00:37:50.610 --> 00:37:52.965
So if the Yankees win he gets
two hundred thousand,

00:37:52.965 --> 00:37:55.699
but if the Yankees lose he
loses three hundred thousand.

00:37:55.699 --> 00:37:59.119
So 3:2 odds he's willing to bet
on the Yankees winning the

00:37:59.119 --> 00:37:59.659
series.
 

00:37:59.659 --> 00:38:00.963
Well, you say,
"This guy's sort of a

00:38:00.963 --> 00:38:01.420
sucker here.
 

00:38:01.420 --> 00:38:02.840
I can take big advantage of him.
 

00:38:02.840 --> 00:38:07.003
On the other hand it's a lot of
money, two hundred thousand I

00:38:07.003 --> 00:38:10.750
might lose if I have to pay off
and the Yankees win.

00:38:10.750 --> 00:38:15.670
So even though I think that my
expected profit is positive,

00:38:15.670 --> 00:38:17.505
because he's putting up three
hundred thousand to make only

00:38:17.505 --> 00:38:18.710
two hundred when they're even
odds,

00:38:18.710 --> 00:38:22.150
in fact--the fact is it's such
a big number I'm a little

00:38:22.150 --> 00:38:23.840
worried about that."
 

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:25.639
So what do you do?
 

00:38:25.639 --> 00:38:26.670
So what can you do?
 

00:38:26.670 --> 00:38:30.481
You've got these friends who
are willing to bet at even odds

00:38:30.481 --> 00:38:33.655
each game by game,
so how much money--Presumably

00:38:33.655 --> 00:38:37.539
the first night you're going to
bet with one of your friends.

00:38:37.539 --> 00:38:39.300
You take the guy's bet,
the customer,

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:41.159
you take his three hundred
thousand.

00:38:41.159 --> 00:38:44.059
You promise to deliver him five
hundred back if the Yankees win

00:38:44.059 --> 00:38:45.789
and to keep it if the Yankees
lose.

00:38:45.789 --> 00:38:48.018
What should you do with your
friends?

00:38:48.018 --> 00:38:50.550
Should you bet on the Yankees
with your friends?

00:38:50.550 --> 00:38:53.382
Should you bet on the Dodgers
with your friends and how much

00:38:53.382 --> 00:38:55.590
should you bet at even odds the
first night?

00:38:55.590 --> 00:38:58.793
So the answer is,
well, I don't want to give all

00:38:58.793 --> 00:39:01.173
the answer now,
but so there's a way of

00:39:01.173 --> 00:39:03.934
skillfully betting with your
friends and not betting two

00:39:03.934 --> 00:39:06.594
hundred or three hundred
thousand the first night with

00:39:06.594 --> 00:39:08.150
your friends at even odds.
 

00:39:08.150 --> 00:39:09.690
You bet some different number
than that,

00:39:09.690 --> 00:39:12.324
which you'll figure out how
much to bet so that if you keep

00:39:12.324 --> 00:39:15.007
betting through the course of
the World Series you can never

00:39:15.007 --> 00:39:15.780
lose a penny.
 

00:39:15.780 --> 00:39:17.449
How do you know how much that
is?

00:39:17.449 --> 00:39:20.992
Well, that's the kind of clever
thing that these finance guys

00:39:20.992 --> 00:39:23.768
developed and you're going to
know how to do.

00:39:23.768 --> 00:39:25.940
So let's do another example
like that.

00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:28.789
I'm running out of time a
little bit, but an example.

00:39:28.789 --> 00:39:31.476
Suppose there's a deck of
cards, twenty-six red and

00:39:31.476 --> 00:39:32.820
twenty-six black cards.
 

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:34.300
Somebody offers to play a game
with you.

00:39:34.300 --> 00:39:37.929
They say, "If you want to
pick a card and it's black I'll

00:39:37.929 --> 00:39:39.119
give you a dollar.
 

00:39:39.119 --> 00:39:41.190
If it's red you give me a
dollar."

00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:42.931
So if I'm picking,
I'm in the black,

00:39:42.931 --> 00:39:44.873
I get a dollar,
it's in the red I lose a

00:39:44.873 --> 00:39:47.760
dollar, I have to throw away the
card after I pick it.

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:49.902
The guy says,
"By the way,

00:39:49.902 --> 00:39:52.690
you can quit whenever you
want."

00:39:52.690 --> 00:39:55.349
So should you pick the first
card?

00:39:55.349 --> 00:39:59.449
It looks like an even chance of
winning or losing.

00:39:59.449 --> 00:40:01.777
Let's say you pick the first
card, it's black,

00:40:01.777 --> 00:40:02.760
you win a dollar.
 

00:40:02.760 --> 00:40:06.094
Now the guy says,
"Do you want to do it

00:40:06.094 --> 00:40:07.179
again?"
 

00:40:07.179 --> 00:40:09.949
You picked a black one so
there's twenty-six red left and

00:40:09.949 --> 00:40:10.940
twenty-five black.
 

00:40:10.940 --> 00:40:13.280
So now the deck is stacked
against you.

00:40:13.280 --> 00:40:15.659
Should you pick another card?
 

00:40:15.659 --> 00:40:18.059
Well, it doesn't sound like you
should pick another card.

00:40:18.059 --> 00:40:21.871
But you should pick another
card and I can even tell you how

00:40:21.871 --> 00:40:23.230
many cards to pick.
 

00:40:23.230 --> 00:40:25.405
Even if you keep getting blacks
you should keep picking and

00:40:25.405 --> 00:40:25.780
picking.
 

00:40:25.780 --> 00:40:26.719
So how could that be?
 

00:40:26.719 --> 00:40:27.909
It sounds kind of shocking.
 

00:40:27.909 --> 00:40:31.251
Well, it's going to turn out to
be very simple for you to solve

00:40:31.251 --> 00:40:32.869
half way through the course.
 

00:40:32.869 --> 00:40:35.800
So, a more basic question.
 

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:39.460
There are thirty year mortgages
now you can get for five and

00:40:39.460 --> 00:40:41.510
three-quarter percent interest.
 

00:40:41.510 --> 00:40:45.327
There are fifteen-year
mortgages you can get for less,

00:40:45.327 --> 00:40:48.280
like five point three percent
interest.

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:49.059
One's lower than the other.
 

00:40:49.059 --> 00:40:50.751
Should you take the
fifteen-year mortgage or the

00:40:50.751 --> 00:40:51.579
thirty year mortgage?
 

00:40:51.579 --> 00:40:52.960
How do you even think about
that?

00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:57.929
Why do they offer one at a
lower price than the other?

00:40:57.929 --> 00:41:00.539
One more example,
suppose you're a bank and you

00:41:00.539 --> 00:41:02.130
hold a bunch of mortgages.
 

00:41:02.130 --> 00:41:04.697
That means the people in the
houses, you've lent them the

00:41:04.697 --> 00:41:06.670
money, they're promising to pay
you back.

00:41:06.670 --> 00:41:09.706
And you value all those
mortgages at a hundred million

00:41:09.706 --> 00:41:10.280
dollars.
 

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:11.510
The interest rates go down.
 

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:12.840
The government lowers the
interest rates.

00:41:12.840 --> 00:41:15.260
Half of them take advantage to
refinance.

00:41:15.260 --> 00:41:18.199
They pay you back what they owe
and they refinance into a new

00:41:18.199 --> 00:41:18.739
mortgage.
 

00:41:18.739 --> 00:41:20.829
So now you've only got half the
people left.

00:41:20.829 --> 00:41:22.675
Let's say all the people had
the same size mortgage and

00:41:22.675 --> 00:41:23.119
everything.
 

00:41:23.119 --> 00:41:24.349
Half the people are left.
 

00:41:24.349 --> 00:41:28.498
That shrunken pool,
half as big as the original

00:41:28.498 --> 00:41:30.771
pool,
is that worth fifty-million,

00:41:30.771 --> 00:41:33.847
half of what it was before,
or more than fifty-million,

00:41:33.847 --> 00:41:35.369
or less than fifty-million?
 

00:41:35.369 --> 00:41:37.119
How would you decide that?
 

00:41:37.119 --> 00:41:40.760
Again, this is a question which
might be a little puzzling now,

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:44.438
but actually you should be able
to get the sign of that today

00:41:44.438 --> 00:41:47.659
even,
and we'll start to analyze it.

00:41:47.659 --> 00:41:49.559
So that's what mortgage traders
have to do.

00:41:49.559 --> 00:41:51.849
They see interest rates went
down.

00:41:51.849 --> 00:41:53.260
A bunch of people acted.
 

00:41:53.260 --> 00:41:55.451
The people who are left in the
pool are different from the

00:41:55.451 --> 00:41:56.719
people who started in the pool.
 

00:41:56.719 --> 00:42:01.599
Now we've got to revalue
everything and rethink it all,

00:42:01.599 --> 00:42:04.039
so how should we do that?
 

00:42:04.039 --> 00:42:06.757
Let's say you run a hedge fund
and some investor comes to you

00:42:06.757 --> 00:42:08.659
and says, "Oh,
things are terrible.

00:42:08.659 --> 00:42:13.360
Look at all the money you lost
for me last year.

00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:16.112
I know you're doing great this
year and you've made it all back

00:42:16.112 --> 00:42:18.420
that you lost last year,
but I don't want to run that

00:42:18.420 --> 00:42:18.820
risk.
 

00:42:18.820 --> 00:42:21.429
So I want to give you my money,
a billion dollars,

00:42:21.429 --> 00:42:23.940
I want to get these superior
returns you seem to earn,

00:42:23.940 --> 00:42:27.780
but you have to guarantee that
you don't lose me a penny.

00:42:27.780 --> 00:42:29.139
I don't want to run any risk.
 

00:42:29.139 --> 00:42:32.355
I want a principal guarantee
(it's called) that when I give

00:42:32.355 --> 00:42:35.239
you a hundred dollars you'll
always return my hundred

00:42:35.239 --> 00:42:36.867
dollars,
and hopefully much more,

00:42:36.867 --> 00:42:38.570
but never less than a hundred
dollars."

00:42:38.570 --> 00:42:40.570
So is there any way to do that?
 

00:42:40.570 --> 00:42:42.420
You know that you've got a
great strategy,

00:42:42.420 --> 00:42:43.639
but of course it's risky.
 

00:42:43.639 --> 00:42:44.389
You could lose money.
 

00:42:44.389 --> 00:42:46.239
You've lost money a bunch of
times before.

00:42:46.239 --> 00:42:49.489
So how can you guarantee the
guy that he'll get all his money

00:42:49.489 --> 00:42:52.090
back and still have room to run
your strategy?

00:42:52.090 --> 00:42:54.458
Well, it sounds like you can't
do it, but of course a lot of

00:42:54.458 --> 00:42:56.989
people want to invest that way,
so there must be a way to do.

00:42:56.989 --> 00:43:00.699
So you'll figure out--we'll
learn how to do that.

00:43:00.699 --> 00:43:02.530
So, three more short ones.
 

00:43:02.530 --> 00:43:05.659
A scientist discovers a
potential cure for AIDS.

00:43:05.659 --> 00:43:08.380
If it works he's going to make
a fortune.

00:43:08.380 --> 00:43:09.360
He started a company.
 

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:11.248
He's a Yale scientist,
he's--medical school,

00:43:11.248 --> 00:43:12.610
started this startup company.
 

00:43:12.610 --> 00:43:14.489
Yale, of course,
is going to take all his

00:43:14.489 --> 00:43:17.307
profits, but anyway it's his
startup company and if his thing

00:43:17.307 --> 00:43:19.469
really works he's going to make
a fortune.

00:43:19.469 --> 00:43:22.280
If it doesn't work it's going
to be totally zero.

00:43:22.280 --> 00:43:24.210
You calculate,
and let's say you believe your

00:43:24.210 --> 00:43:26.592
calculation,
that the expected profits that

00:43:26.592 --> 00:43:29.449
he'll make if it works,
the probability of it working

00:43:29.449 --> 00:43:32.376
times the profit,
that expected profit is equal

00:43:32.376 --> 00:43:35.340
to the profits of all of General
Electric.

00:43:35.340 --> 00:43:38.230
Should his company be worth
more than General Electric,

00:43:38.230 --> 00:43:42.713
the same as General Electric,
or less than General Electric

00:43:42.713 --> 00:43:46.039
since it's got the same expected
profits?

00:43:46.039 --> 00:43:49.590
Well, I can tell you the answer
to this one because I think most

00:43:49.590 --> 00:43:51.338
of you would think,
first you'd think,

00:43:51.338 --> 00:43:52.300
"Well, maybe the
same."

00:43:52.300 --> 00:43:53.574
Then you'd say,
"Well, this AIDS thing

00:43:53.574 --> 00:43:54.059
it's so risky.
 

00:43:54.059 --> 00:43:56.000
It's either going to be way up
here or nothing,

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:57.856
and that's so risky,
and General Electric is so

00:43:57.856 --> 00:44:00.617
solid,
probably General Electric is

00:44:00.617 --> 00:44:02.159
worth more."
 

00:44:02.159 --> 00:44:05.510
But the answer is the AIDS
Company is worth more.

00:44:05.510 --> 00:44:07.090
So how could that be?
 

00:44:07.090 --> 00:44:09.994
So another question,
suppose you believed in this

00:44:09.994 --> 00:44:13.625
efficient market stuff and you
rank all the stocks at the end

00:44:13.625 --> 00:44:17.315
of this year from top to bottom
of which stock had the highest

00:44:17.315 --> 00:44:18.949
return over the year.
 

00:44:18.949 --> 00:44:21.780
It's 2010, let's say 2010,
this year's a weird year.

00:44:21.780 --> 00:44:23.280
So let's say you do it in 2010.
 

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:26.829
All the stocks the highest
return to the lowest return.

00:44:26.829 --> 00:44:30.525
Now, suppose you did the same
thing in 2011 with the same

00:44:30.525 --> 00:44:31.119
stocks?
 

00:44:31.119 --> 00:44:35.224
Would you expect to get the
same order, or the reverse

00:44:35.224 --> 00:44:37.159
order, or random order?
 

00:44:37.159 --> 00:44:39.286
Now again, if you believe in
efficient markets and the

00:44:39.286 --> 00:44:43.483
market's really functioning,
the prices are fair and all,

00:44:43.483 --> 00:44:47.735
I'll bet most of you will say,
you won't know,

00:44:47.735 --> 00:44:50.889
but you might say it should be
random the next time,

00:44:50.889 --> 00:44:54.590
because firms only did better
or worse by luck,

00:44:54.590 --> 00:44:55.989
but that's not right either.
 

00:44:55.989 --> 00:44:59.833
So you're going to know how to
answer that question by the end

00:44:59.833 --> 00:45:00.780
of the class.
 

00:45:00.780 --> 00:45:02.983
One last one,
the Yale endowment over the

00:45:02.983 --> 00:45:06.347
last fifteen years has gotten
something like a fifteen percent

00:45:06.347 --> 00:45:07.559
annualized return.
 

00:45:07.559 --> 00:45:09.304
A hedge fund,
that I won't name,

00:45:09.304 --> 00:45:12.735
has gotten eleven percent over
the last fifteen years counting

00:45:12.735 --> 00:45:14.929
all its losses and stuff like
that.

00:45:14.929 --> 00:45:19.114
So is it obvious that the Yale
endowment has done better than

00:45:19.114 --> 00:45:20.300
the hedge fund?
 

00:45:20.300 --> 00:45:23.097
Would you say that the Yale
manager is better than the hedge

00:45:23.097 --> 00:45:23.809
fund manager?
 

00:45:23.809 --> 00:45:25.510
Its return was fifteen percent.
 

00:45:25.510 --> 00:45:27.340
The hedge fund only got eleven
percent.

00:45:27.340 --> 00:45:31.208
So I'm asking the question,
and I would say that David

00:45:31.208 --> 00:45:35.659
Swensen would think about it the
same way I think about it.

00:45:35.659 --> 00:45:42.324
So suppose I even told you that
the Yale hedge fund had lower

00:45:42.324 --> 00:45:46.186
volatility--
the Yale hedge fund?--the Yale

00:45:46.186 --> 00:45:50.260
endowment had lower volatility
than the hedge fund,

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:53.704
which it surely does,
would that convince you now

00:45:53.704 --> 00:45:58.083
that the Yale endowment had been
managed better than the hedge

00:45:58.083 --> 00:45:58.730
fund?
 

00:45:58.730 --> 00:46:01.324
Well, we're going to answer
this question again,

00:46:01.324 --> 00:46:04.030
and you're going to see that
the answer's a little

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:04.860
surprising.
 

00:46:04.860 --> 00:46:07.329
It won't be so surprising--I
wouldn't have brought it up

00:46:07.329 --> 00:46:07.869
otherwise.
 

00:46:07.869 --> 00:46:12.170
But anyway, that's the kind of
thing that in finance you're

00:46:12.170 --> 00:46:13.949
taught to think about.
 

00:46:13.949 --> 00:46:16.996
So the crisis of 2007,
which we're going to spend a

00:46:16.996 --> 00:46:20.347
long time talking about,
I just want to get back to that

00:46:20.347 --> 00:46:21.079
subject.
 

00:46:21.079 --> 00:46:24.860
So that list of questions were
the kinds of things that I used

00:46:24.860 --> 00:46:28.516
to teach for years before I was
confident about my theory of

00:46:28.516 --> 00:46:30.153
crises,
and this is the kind of

00:46:30.153 --> 00:46:32.369
questions you have to face all
the time in hedge funds,

00:46:32.369 --> 00:46:34.525
and decisions you have to make,
and things you have to tell

00:46:34.525 --> 00:46:37.039
investors,
and so that's the basic part of

00:46:37.039 --> 00:46:39.969
the course,
but I want to say more.

00:46:39.969 --> 00:46:43.099
So I want to talk about the
crisis of 2007-2009.

00:46:43.099 --> 00:46:45.210
It started as a mortgage crisis.
 

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:47.362
Now, how could it be that
everything goes wrong in

00:46:47.362 --> 00:46:47.889
mortgages?
 

00:46:47.889 --> 00:46:49.639
I mean, they're four thousand
years old.

00:46:49.639 --> 00:46:51.289
The Babylonians invented
mortgages.

